German state Premier Armin Laschet took the first step toward becoming Chancellor Angela Merkel’s successor after he was elected party leader of the conservative Christian Democrats. Fifty-nine-year-old Laschet saw off a challenge from wealthy corporate lawyer, Friedrich Merz, in a run-off vote at the CDU’s first-ever digital party convention. Laschet is the Premier of North Rhine Westphalia, the most populous state in Germany. ABUJA DOCTOR REVEALS HOW MOST NIGERIA MEN ARE NOW OVERCOMING TERRIBLE BEDROOM PERFORMANCE DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. DON'T BE A VICTIM! He has said he is committed to continuing Merkel’s centrist policies and was seen as the party establishment’s candidate. He won 521 of the votes by 991 delegates. Merz was backed by 466 delegates. Four delegates abstained. U.S. Attorney Says No Direct Evidence Of Kidnapping Plot At Capitol Biden To Mount Federal Vaccination Campaign A third candidate, foreign policy expert, Norbert Roettgen, was eliminated in the first round of voting. The vote comes at the start of a crucial year in German politics, with national elections set for September. Merkel plans to retire at the end of her current fourth term. Traditionally, the CDU leader spearheads  election campaign as chancellor candidate for the heavyweight party and its Bavarian-based allies, the Christian Social Union (CSU). (dpa/NAN)